kcpRS analysis using runMean¶

Using kcpRS function, we can run a change point detection analysis. You should specify the next arguments:

  • RS_fun: the metric used which can be runMean, runVar, runAR and runCorr. This is also possible to create your own metric.
  • RS_name: give a name to the analysis.
  • wsize: specify the size of the window.
  • nperm: number of permutations used in the permutation test.
  • Kmax: maximum number of change points.
  • alpha: significance level of the permutation test
  • varTest: if set to FALSE, only the variance DROP test is implemented, and if set to TRUE, both the variance test and the variance DROP tests are implemented.
  • ncpu: the number of CPU core used. Specifying detectCores(), your computer will use all its cores.

See more here: https://rdrr.io/cran/kcpRS/man/kcpRS.html

In [17]:

How many change points?¶

How many number of change points should it be extracted from the analysis? In the kcpRS, the decision is based on two methods:

  • Permutation test
  • Grid search through C penality

A short precision: kcpRS.mod (from "FUN_kcpRS_mod.R" script) is a modified function that have been created just for a matter of demonstration in this notebook. It allows to extract the results of the permutation test and the grid search to plot them. Do not use it in your own analysis!

Time series plot¶

We will use the dataset from Sels et al., 2021. In a first part, for a demonstration purpose, we will only use the data from the couple 3. Note that the change point detection method can be run only one dyad at a time.

The variables of the database are the following:

  • Couple: the couple's number in the experiment.
  • type: there is two phases in the experiment. PC correspond to the positive interaction part and NC to the negative interaction one.
  • obs: is the number of observation during the experiment.
  • dial.1 are measurement of the first partner.
  • dial.2 on the second one.

Over one dyad¶

In Sels et al., 2021, three types of similarities in dyad context and three measurements associated to each one are defined:

  • Correlation: similarities in how partners’ emotional experiences fluctuate throughout time (shape similarity)
  • Instantaneous derivative matching (IDM): similarities in the variance of these experiences (scatter similarity) \begin{equation} IDM = \frac{1}{T} \sum_{t=1}^{T} |(a_{t-1} - a_{t}) - (b_{t-1} - b_{t})| \end{equation}
  • Signal matching (SM): similarities in the average intensity of their experiences (level similarity) \begin{equation} SM = \frac{1}{T} \sum_{t=1}^{T} |a_{t} - b_{t}| \end{equation}

Creating running function: runIDM and runSM¶

For the IDM and the SM scores, you should create a new running function: runIDM and runSM. The code below come from the supplementary material of Sels et al., 2021.

In [27]:
runIDM <- function(data, wsize = 25) {
  data <- as.data.frame(data)
  labs <- colnames(data)
  data <- as.matrix(data)
  N <- nrow(data)
  wstep <- 1
  windows <- floor(((N - wsize)/wstep) + 1)
  
  # define scores
  X <- data[,1]
  Y <- data[,2]
  
  # 1. difference between each time point and the subsequent time point
  # 2. compare the corresponding slopes of the two subjects at each time point
  absDiff <- matrix(NA, nrow=(length(X)-1), ncol=1)
  for (i in 1:length(absDiff)) {
    absDiff[i] <- abs((X[i+1] - X[i]) - (Y[i+1] - Y[i]))
  }
  
  # 3. running average slope difference
  RunIDM_TS <- roll_mean(absDiff, width = wsize)
  
  RunIDM_TS <- RunIDM_TS[seq(wsize, wsize + windows - 2, 
                             wstep), ]
  RunIDM_TS <- as.data.frame(RunIDM_TS)
  colnames(RunIDM_TS) <- paste0(labs[1], "&", labs[2])
  return(RunIDM_TS)
}
In [28]:
# SM: Signal matching
runSM <- function(data, wsize = 25) {
  data <- as.data.frame(data)
  labs <- colnames(data)
  data <- as.matrix(data)
  N <- nrow(data)
  wstep <- 1
  windows <- floor(((N - wsize)/wstep) + 1)
  
  # define scores
  X <- data[,1]  # Indiv1
  Y <- data[,2]  # Indiv 2
  
  # 1. calculate absolute difference between the score of Indiv1 and the score 
  # of Indiv2 at each time point
  absDiff <- matrix(NA, nrow=length(X), ncol=1)
  for (i in 1:length(X)) {
    absDiff[i] <- abs(X[i] - Y[i])
  }
  
  # 2. running average absolute difference
  RunSM_TS <- roll_mean(absDiff, width = wsize)
  
  RunSM_TS <- RunSM_TS[seq(wsize, wsize + windows - 1, 
                           wstep), ]
  RunSM_TS <- as.data.frame(RunSM_TS)
  colnames(RunSM_TS) <- paste0(labs[1], "&", labs[2])
  return(RunSM_TS)
}

Sensitive test¶

Over all dyads¶

Finally, we can run the kcpRS function for every couple and running statistic selected (i.e., correlation, IDM, MS). We can plot the results and see the different change points detected for every couple. Be careful, this operation takes a lot of time!

In [37]:
library(tictoc)
tic()

data_dyad_tab = data_dyad # %>% filter(Couple %in% c(1:3))
data_results = data.frame()

# For every couple
for (id in unique(data_dyad_tab$Couple)){
    
    dt = data_dyad_tab %>% filter(Couple == id) %>% select(dial.1, dial.2)

    # Corr
    kcpRS_corr = kcpRS(data = dt, RS_fun = runCorr, RS_name = "Correlation", 
                       wsize = 25, nperm = 1000, Kmax = 10, alpha = .05, varTest = FALSE, 
                       ncpu = detectCores())
    corr_res = data.frame(couple = rep(id,10), type = rep("corr",10), time = c(kcpRS_corr$changePoints, rep(NA,10 - length(kcpRS_corr$changePoints)))) 
    
    # IDM
    kcpRS_IDM = kcpRS(data = dt, RS_fun = runIDM, RS_name = "IDM", 
                      wsize = 25, nperm = 1000, Kmax = 10, alpha = .05, varTest = FALSE, 
                      ncpu = detectCores())
    IDM_res = data.frame(couple = rep(id,10), type = rep("IDM",10), time = c(kcpRS_IDM$changePoints, rep(NA,10 - length(kcpRS_IDM$changePoints)))) 
    
    # SM
    kcpRS_SM = kcpRS(data = dt, RS_fun = runSM, RS_name = "SM", 
                              wsize = 25, nperm = 1000, Kmax = 10, alpha = .05, varTest = FALSE, 
                              ncpu = detectCores())
    SM_res = data.frame(couple = rep(id,10), type = rep("SM",10), time = c(kcpRS_SM$changePoints, rep(NA,10 - length(kcpRS_SM$changePoints)))) 
    
    # Save data
    data_results = bind_rows(data_results, corr_res, IDM_res, SM_res)

}
